   <text>
      <body>
         
            
               <p>A native of <placeName>London</placeName> and a slave-trader, Newton had a
                  conversion experience on board his ship in <date when="1748-03">March 1748</date>.
                  About <date when="1756">1756</date> he abandoned his former trade and became
                  active in the Evangelical revival. He turned to supporting himself as a tax
                  collector in the port of <placeName>Liverpool</placeName>, while seeking
                  ordination. He was finally ordained in <date when="1764">1764</date> and became
                  vicar at <placeName>Olney</placeName>. He is best known for his hymns and his
                  writings against the slave trade. Newton married <persName>Mary Catlett</persName>
                  in <date when="1750">1750</date>. See <hi rend="italic">DEB</hi>, 824–25; <hi rend="italic">ODNB</hi>; and Vickers, <hi rend="italic">Dictionary</hi>,
                  253.</p>
            
         
